<p>To generate the payment identifier hash, you use the salt provided by IdentityMind, to generate a SHA-1 hash for the non-masked, clear text payment identifier, and convert the byte array of the hash to a hexadecimal string. The hash should be included in the JSON string of the request.</p>
<blockquote class="callout callout_info" theme="📘"><h3 class="callout-heading false"><span class="callout-icon">📘</span><p>Hashing Salt</p></h3><p>Please contact IdentityMind Support to get the salt value.</p></blockquote>
<p>If you have a function <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">sha1(String s)</span></code> that takes a string s and return the SHA-1 hash of the string in hex, you would concatenate the salt and the payment identifier and pass that to the function to get the hash.</p>
<blockquote class="callout callout_warn" theme="🚧"><h3 class="callout-heading false"><span class="callout-icon">🚧</span><p>Hash the complete identifier</p></h3><p>The hash must be of the full card number, not a masked or tokenized representation. If you use other languages, please see “Credit Card Number Hash”.</p><p>If the payment instrument identifier isn't available to hash, we ask that you concatenate the first name (lowercase), last name (lowercase), the first six digits of the identifier and the last four digits of the card number, and then hash the value.</p></blockquote>
<p>To illustrate this algorithm, the following sample produces such a hash of a credit card number using the standard Java SHA-1 hashing utility or Python.</p>
<div class="CodeTabs CodeTabs_initial"><div class="CodeTabs-toolbar"><button type="button">Java</button><button type="button">Python</button></div><div class="CodeTabs-inner"><pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-java" data-lang="java" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><div class="cm-s-neo"><span class="cm-keyword">import</span> <span class="cm-variable">java</span>.<span class="cm-variable">security</span>.<span class="cm-variable">MessageDigest</span>;
<span class="cm-keyword">import</span> <span class="cm-variable">java</span>.<span class="cm-variable">security</span>.<span class="cm-variable">NoSuchAlgorithmException</span>;

<span class="cm-comment">/**</span>
 <span class="cm-comment">* Demonstration of the credit card number hashing using standard Java classes.</span>
 <span class="cm-comment">* If you are in Java then using the CreditCardUtils class is likely the </span>
 <span class="cm-comment">* better option.  </span>
 <span class="cm-comment">*/</span>
<span class="cm-keyword">public</span> <span class="cm-keyword">class</span> <span class="cm-def">CCNHashing</span> {

    <span class="cm-keyword">private</span> <span class="cm-keyword">static</span> <span class="cm-keyword">final</span> <span class="cm-type">String</span> <span class="cm-variable">CCN</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-string">"4111 1111 1111 1111"</span>;

    <span class="cm-keyword">public</span> <span class="cm-keyword">static</span> <span class="cm-type">void</span> <span class="cm-variable">main</span>(<span class="cm-type">String</span>[] <span class="cm-variable">args</span>) {

        <span class="cm-type">String</span> <span class="cm-variable">input</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">CCN</span>;

        <span class="cm-keyword">if</span> (<span class="cm-variable">args</span>.<span class="cm-variable">length</span> <span class="cm-operator">==</span> <span class="cm-number">1</span>)
            <span class="cm-variable">input</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">args</span>[<span class="cm-number">0</span>];

        <span class="cm-variable">CCNHashing</span> <span class="cm-variable">hashing</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-keyword">new</span> <span class="cm-variable">CCNHashing</span>();

        <span class="cm-type">String</span> <span class="cm-variable">token</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">hashing</span>.<span class="cm-variable">generateCardToken</span>(<span class="cm-variable">input</span>);

        <span class="cm-type">String</span> <span class="cm-variable">hash</span>  <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">hashing</span>.<span class="cm-variable">generateFullCardHash</span>(<span class="cm-variable">input</span>);

        <span class="cm-variable">System</span>.<span class="cm-variable">out</span>.<span class="cm-variable">println</span>(<span class="cm-type">String</span>.<span class="cm-variable">format</span>(<span class="cm-string">"Input Card \"%s\" tokenized as %s and hashed to %s"</span>,
                                         <span class="cm-variable">input</span>,
                                         <span class="cm-variable">token</span>,
                                         <span class="cm-variable">hash</span>));
    }

    <span class="cm-comment">/**</span>
     <span class="cm-comment">* Utility method for generating a credit card token - 411111XXXXXX1111</span>
     <span class="cm-comment">* @param ccn  The credit card number to tokenize</span>
     <span class="cm-comment">*/</span>
    <span class="cm-keyword">private</span> <span class="cm-type">String</span> <span class="cm-variable">generateCardToken</span>(<span class="cm-type">String</span> <span class="cm-variable">ccn</span>) {

        <span class="cm-comment">// normalize the credit card number by removing white space</span>
        <span class="cm-type">String</span> <span class="cm-variable">normalized</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">ccn</span>.<span class="cm-variable">replaceAll</span>(<span class="cm-string">"[^a-zA-Z0-9]"</span>, <span class="cm-string">""</span>);

        <span class="cm-keyword">if</span> (<span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>.<span class="cm-variable">length</span>() <span class="cm-operator">==</span> <span class="cm-number">15</span> <span class="cm-operator">||</span> <span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>.<span class="cm-variable">length</span>() <span class="cm-operator">==</span> <span class="cm-number">16</span>) {
            <span class="cm-keyword">return</span> <span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>.<span class="cm-variable">substring</span>(<span class="cm-number">0</span>, <span class="cm-number">6</span>) <span class="cm-operator">+</span> <span class="cm-string">"XXXXXX"</span> <span class="cm-operator">+</span> <span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>.<span class="cm-variable">substring</span>(<span class="cm-number">12</span>, <span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>.<span class="cm-variable">length</span>());
        } <span class="cm-keyword">else</span> {
            <span class="cm-keyword">throw</span> <span class="cm-keyword">new</span> <span class="cm-variable">IllegalArgumentException</span>(<span class="cm-string">"card number did not normalize to a 15 or 16 digit number"</span>);
        }
    }

    <span class="cm-comment">/**</span>
     <span class="cm-comment">* Generate a hash of the provided credit card number using a well defined</span>
     <span class="cm-comment">* salt.   The hash can be defined as</span>
     <span class="cm-comment">*   hexString ( SHA-1 ( salt + CCN ) )</span>
     <span class="cm-comment">*</span>
     <span class="cm-comment">* @param ccn the card number to be hashed</span>
     <span class="cm-comment">* @return a 40 character hex string representation of the hashed card</span>
     <span class="cm-comment">*/</span>
    <span class="cm-keyword">private</span> <span class="cm-type">String</span> <span class="cm-variable">generateFullCardHash</span>(<span class="cm-type">String</span> <span class="cm-variable">ccn</span>) {
 
        <span class="cm-comment">// sample salt value.  The actual salt will be provided by IdentityMind</span>
        <span class="cm-comment">// support</span>
        <span class="cm-type">byte</span>[] <span class="cm-variable">salt</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> {<span class="cm-number">0x00</span>, <span class="cm-number">0x00</span>, <span class="cm-number">0x00</span>, <span class="cm-number">0x00</span>, <span class="cm-number">0x00</span>, <span class="cm-number">0x00</span>, <span class="cm-number">0x00</span>, <span class="cm-number">0x00</span>, <span class="cm-number">0x00</span>, <span class="cm-number">0x00</span>, <span class="cm-number">0x00</span>, <span class="cm-number">0x00</span>};

        <span class="cm-comment">// normalize the credit card number by removing white space</span>
        <span class="cm-type">String</span> <span class="cm-variable">normalized</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">ccn</span>.<span class="cm-variable">replaceAll</span>(<span class="cm-string">"[^a-zA-Z0-9]"</span>, <span class="cm-string">""</span>);

        <span class="cm-comment">// get a message digester for SHA-1</span>
        <span class="cm-variable">MessageDigest</span> <span class="cm-variable">md</span>;
        <span class="cm-keyword">try</span> {
            <span class="cm-variable">md</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">MessageDigest</span>.<span class="cm-variable">getInstance</span>(<span class="cm-string">"SHA-1"</span>);
        } <span class="cm-keyword">catch</span> (<span class="cm-variable">NoSuchAlgorithmException</span> <span class="cm-variable">e</span>) {
            <span class="cm-keyword">throw</span> <span class="cm-keyword">new</span> <span class="cm-variable">RuntimeException</span>(<span class="cm-variable">e</span>);
        }

        <span class="cm-comment">// the first add the salt bytes to the digest</span>
        <span class="cm-variable">md</span>.<span class="cm-variable">update</span>(<span class="cm-variable">salt</span>);
        <span class="cm-comment">// now add the normalized CCN and hash it</span>
        <span class="cm-keyword">final</span> <span class="cm-type">byte</span>[] <span class="cm-variable">data</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">md</span>.<span class="cm-variable">digest</span>(<span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>.<span class="cm-variable">getBytes</span>());

        <span class="cm-comment">// finally return a hex string representation</span>
        <span class="cm-keyword">return</span> <span class="cm-variable">bytesToHex</span>(<span class="cm-variable">data</span>);
    }

    <span class="cm-keyword">private</span> <span class="cm-keyword">final</span> <span class="cm-type">char</span>[] <span class="cm-variable">DIGITS</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> {
            <span class="cm-string">'0'</span>, <span class="cm-string">'1'</span>, <span class="cm-string">'2'</span>, <span class="cm-string">'3'</span>, <span class="cm-string">'4'</span>, <span class="cm-string">'5'</span>, <span class="cm-string">'6'</span>, <span class="cm-string">'7'</span>,
            <span class="cm-string">'8'</span>, <span class="cm-string">'9'</span>, <span class="cm-string">'a'</span>, <span class="cm-string">'b'</span>, <span class="cm-string">'c'</span>, <span class="cm-string">'d'</span>, <span class="cm-string">'e'</span>, <span class="cm-string">'f'</span>
    };

    <span class="cm-keyword">public</span> <span class="cm-type">String</span> <span class="cm-variable">bytesToHex</span>(<span class="cm-type">byte</span>[] <span class="cm-variable">data</span>) {
        <span class="cm-type">int</span> <span class="cm-variable">l</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">data</span>.<span class="cm-variable">length</span>;
        <span class="cm-type">char</span>[] <span class="cm-variable">out</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-keyword">new</span> <span class="cm-type">char</span>[<span class="cm-variable">l</span> <span class="cm-operator">&lt;&lt;</span> <span class="cm-number">1</span>];
        <span class="cm-comment">// two characters form the hex value.</span>
        <span class="cm-keyword">for</span> (<span class="cm-type">int</span> <span class="cm-variable">i</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-number">0</span>, <span class="cm-variable">j</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-number">0</span>; <span class="cm-variable">i</span> <span class="cm-operator">&lt;</span> <span class="cm-variable">l</span>; <span class="cm-variable">i</span><span class="cm-operator">++</span>) {
            <span class="cm-variable">out</span>[<span class="cm-variable">j</span><span class="cm-operator">++</span>] <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">DIGITS</span>[(<span class="cm-number">0xF0</span> <span class="cm-operator">&amp;</span> <span class="cm-variable">data</span>[<span class="cm-variable">i</span>]) <span class="cm-operator">&gt;&gt;&gt;</span> <span class="cm-number">4</span>];
            <span class="cm-variable">out</span>[<span class="cm-variable">j</span><span class="cm-operator">++</span>] <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">DIGITS</span>[<span class="cm-number">0x0F</span> <span class="cm-operator">&amp;</span> <span class="cm-variable">data</span>[<span class="cm-variable">i</span>]];
        }
        <span class="cm-keyword">return</span> <span class="cm-keyword">new</span> <span class="cm-type">String</span>(<span class="cm-variable">out</span>);
    }
}
</div></code></pre><pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-python" data-lang="python" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><div class="cm-s-neo"><span class="cm-keyword">import</span> <span class="cm-variable">hashlib</span>
<span class="cm-keyword">import</span> <span class="cm-variable">re</span>

<span class="cm-variable">SALT</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-string">'\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00\x00'</span>


<span class="cm-keyword">def</span> <span class="cm-def">normalize_credit_card_number</span>(<span class="cm-variable">card_number</span>):
    <span class="cm-string">"""</span>
<span class="cm-string">    Normalizes credit card number, removes spaces and punctuation from the</span>
<span class="cm-string">    provided string. For example, an input of "4123 1234 1234 1234" returns</span>
<span class="cm-string">    "4123123412341234".</span>
<span class="cm-string">    """</span>

    <span class="cm-variable">normalized</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">normalize_payment_identifier</span>(<span class="cm-variable">card_number</span>)
    <span class="cm-keyword">if</span> <span class="cm-builtin">len</span>(<span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>) <span class="cm-operator">&lt;</span> <span class="cm-number">15</span> <span class="cm-keyword">or</span> <span class="cm-builtin">len</span>(<span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>) <span class="cm-operator">&gt;</span> <span class="cm-number">16</span>:
        <span class="cm-keyword">raise</span> <span class="cm-variable">ValueError</span>(<span class="cm-string">'The given credit card number is invalid'</span>)
    <span class="cm-keyword">return</span> <span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>

<span class="cm-keyword">def</span> <span class="cm-def">normalize_payment_identifier</span>(<span class="cm-variable">identifier</span>):
    <span class="cm-keyword">return</span> <span class="cm-variable">re</span>.<span class="cm-property">sub</span>(<span class="cm-string">r'[^a-zA-Z0-9]'</span>, <span class="cm-string">''</span>, <span class="cm-variable">identifier</span>)

<span class="cm-keyword">def</span> <span class="cm-def">generate_payment_hash</span>(<span class="cm-variable">identifier</span>):
    <span class="cm-variable">m</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">hashlib</span>.<span class="cm-property">sha1</span>(<span class="cm-variable">SALT</span>)
    <span class="cm-variable">m</span>.<span class="cm-property">update</span>(<span class="cm-variable">normalize_payment_identifier</span>(<span class="cm-variable">identifier</span>))
    <span class="cm-keyword">return</span> <span class="cm-variable">m</span>.<span class="cm-property">hexdigest</span>()

<span class="cm-keyword">def</span> <span class="cm-def">generate_credit_card_hash</span>(<span class="cm-variable">card_number</span>):
    <span class="cm-string">"""</span>
<span class="cm-string">    Generate a hash of the provided credit card number using a well defined salt.</span>
<span class="cm-string">    The value of the salt and a complete description of the hashing algorithm is</span>
<span class="cm-string">    available from IdentityMind support.</span>
<span class="cm-string">    """</span>
    <span class="cm-keyword">return</span> <span class="cm-variable">generate_payment_hash</span>(<span class="cm-variable">normalize_credit_card_number</span>(<span class="cm-variable">card_number</span>))

<span class="cm-keyword">def</span> <span class="cm-def">generate_bank_account_hash</span>(<span class="cm-variable">routing_num</span>, <span class="cm-variable">account_num</span>):
    <span class="cm-string">"""</span>
<span class="cm-string">    Generate a hash of the provided routing and account number using a well</span>
<span class="cm-string">    defined salt.  The value of the salt and a complete description of the</span>
<span class="cm-string">    hashing algorithm is available from IdentityMind support.</span>
<span class="cm-string">    """</span>
    <span class="cm-keyword">return</span> <span class="cm-variable">generate_payment_hash</span>(<span class="cm-variable">routing_num</span> <span class="cm-operator">+</span> <span class="cm-variable">account_num</span>)


<span class="cm-keyword">def</span> <span class="cm-def">generate_credit_card_token</span>(<span class="cm-variable">card_number</span>):
    <span class="cm-string">"""</span>
<span class="cm-string">    Generates a credit card token, e.g. 456755XXXXXX8742</span>
<span class="cm-string">    """</span>
    <span class="cm-variable">normalized</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">normalize_credit_card_number</span>(<span class="cm-variable">card_number</span>)

    <span class="cm-keyword">if</span> <span class="cm-builtin">len</span>(<span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>) <span class="cm-operator">==</span> <span class="cm-number">16</span>:
        <span class="cm-keyword">return</span> <span class="cm-string">'%sXXXXXX%s'</span> <span class="cm-operator">%</span> (<span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>[<span class="cm-number">0</span>:<span class="cm-number">6</span>], <span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>[<span class="cm-number">12</span>:<span class="cm-number">16</span>])
    <span class="cm-keyword">else</span>:
        <span class="cm-keyword">return</span> <span class="cm-string">'%sXXXXXX%s'</span> <span class="cm-operator">%</span> (<span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>[<span class="cm-number">0</span>:<span class="cm-number">6</span>], <span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>[<span class="cm-number">11</span>:<span class="cm-number">15</span>])

<span class="cm-keyword">def</span> <span class="cm-def">generate_bank_account_token</span>(<span class="cm-variable">routing_num</span>, <span class="cm-variable">account_num</span>):
    <span class="cm-variable">normalized</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">normalize_payment_identifier</span>(<span class="cm-variable">routing_num</span> <span class="cm-operator">+</span> <span class="cm-variable">account_num</span>)
    <span class="cm-keyword">return</span> <span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>[<span class="cm-number">0</span>:<span class="cm-number">6</span>] <span class="cm-operator">+</span> <span class="cm-string">'XXXXXXXX'</span> <span class="cm-operator">+</span> <span class="cm-variable">normalized</span>[<span class="cm-operator">-</span><span class="cm-number">4</span>:]
</div></code></pre></div></div>
<blockquote class="callout callout_info" theme="📘"><h3 class="callout-heading false"><span class="callout-icon">📘</span><p>Additional protection of payment</p></h3><p>In addition to the salted SHA-1 hash that is used for the transmission of the payment instrument identifier, upon receipt of the data the identifier is encrypted (AES256) and rehashed (SHA256 + salt).</p></blockquote>
<h1 class="heading heading-1 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="credit-card"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-credit-card" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Credit Card</div></h1>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="number-hash"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-number-hash" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Number Hash</div></h2>
<p>To generate the credit card number hash, you use the salt provided by IdentityMind, to generate a SHA-1 hash for the non-masked credit card number, and convert the byte array of the hash to Hexadecimal string. The hash should be included in the JSON string of the request in the field pccn.</p>
<blockquote class="callout callout_info" theme="📘"><h3 class="callout-heading false"><span class="callout-icon">📘</span><p>Sample Value</p></h3><p>For example, the salted credit card number hash for <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">4012012301230123</span></code> is <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">32c1950468af7489efb48c911f9550092ebf34c5</span></code> and <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">3456123434561234</span></code> is <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">2d08556207049e9be35fc614eb22a40160b107bc</span></code>.</p><p> You can include these in your unit tests to verify your hashing implementation is correct.</p></blockquote>
<p>The credit card number hash should be included in the JSON string of the request to IdentityMind Transaction API in the field <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">pccn</span></code>.</p>
<p>For Java, the sample code is in <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">imclientSDK/samplecode/java/REST/TransactionViaREST.java</span></code>, for PHP, the sample code is in <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">imclientSDK/samplecode/php/ednaTransaction.php</span></code>:</p>
<div class="CodeTabs CodeTabs_initial"><div class="CodeTabs-toolbar"><button type="button">Java</button><button type="button">PHP</button></div><div class="CodeTabs-inner"><pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-java" data-lang="java" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><div class="cm-s-neo"><span class="cm-variable">JSONObject</span> <span class="cm-variable">jsonRequest</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-keyword">new</span> <span class="cm-variable">JSONObject</span>();

<span class="cm-comment">// credit card token and hash</span>
<span class="cm-comment">// replace the 2nd parameter below with the actual card number</span>

<span class="cm-variable">CreditCardUtils</span>.<span class="cm-variable">addCreditCardData</span>(<span class="cm-variable">jsonRequest</span>, <span class="cm-string">"4012012301230123"</span>); 

<span class="cm-comment">// the json string generated below will include the token, and hashes generated from the actual number</span>

<span class="cm-type">String</span> <span class="cm-variable">body</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">jsonRequest</span>.<span class="cm-variable">toString</span>(<span class="cm-number">2</span>);
</div></code></pre><pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-php" data-lang="php" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><div class="cm-s-neo"><span class="cm-variable-2">$arr</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-keyword">array</span>();

<span class="cm-comment">/* </span>
<span class="cm-comment">replace the 2nd parameter below with the actual card number</span>
<span class="cm-comment">*/</span>
<span class="cm-variable-2">$arr</span>[<span class="cm-variable">CREDIT_CARD_NUMBER</span>] <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">identitymind_hashCCN</span>(<span class="cm-string">"4012012301230123"</span>);
<span class="cm-variable-2">$arr</span>[<span class="cm-variable">CREDIT_CARD_TOKEN</span>] <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">identitymind_tokenCCN</span>(<span class="cm-string">"4012012301230123"</span>);

<span class="cm-comment">/* </span>
<span class="cm-comment">Turn the array into a JSON string to be used as the body of the POST</span>
<span class="cm-comment">*/</span>
<span class="cm-variable-2">$data</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-builtin">json_encode</span>(<span class="cm-variable-2">$arr</span>);
</div></code></pre></div></div>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="token"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-token" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Token</div></h2>
<p>The credit card number token is the first 6 digits of the actual card number followed by XXXXXX followed by the last 4 digits of the actual card number. For example, the credit card number token for card number 4012012301230123 is 401201XXXXXX0123.  </p>
<blockquote class="callout callout_info" theme="📘"><h3 class="callout-heading false"><span class="callout-icon">📘</span><p>Token</p></h3><p>The masked/tokenized number is only used with the user interface as a label for this Credit Card.  It is unique to you and can be in any format that conforms with your information security constraints.</p></blockquote>
<p>The credit card number token should be included in the JSON string of the request to IdentityMind Transaction API in the field <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">pcct</span></code>.</p>
<div class="CodeTabs CodeTabs_initial"><div class="CodeTabs-toolbar"><button type="button">Java</button><button type="button">PHP</button></div><div class="CodeTabs-inner"><pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-java" data-lang="java" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><div class="cm-s-neo"><span class="cm-variable">JSONObject</span> <span class="cm-variable">jsonRequest</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-keyword">new</span> <span class="cm-variable">JSONObject</span>();

<span class="cm-comment">// bank account hash and token</span>
<span class="cm-variable">BankAccountUtils</span>.<span class="cm-variable">addBankAccountData</span>(<span class="cm-variable">json</span>, <span class="cm-string">"321076479"</span>, <span class="cm-string">"74600015199010"</span>); 

<span class="cm-comment">// the json string generated below will include the token, and hash generated from the actual number</span>
<span class="cm-type">String</span> <span class="cm-variable">body</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">jsonRequest</span>.<span class="cm-variable">toString</span>(<span class="cm-number">2</span>);
</div></code></pre><pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-php" data-lang="php" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><div class="cm-s-neo"><span class="cm-variable-2">$arr</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-keyword">array</span>();

<span class="cm-comment">/* replace the 2nd parameter below with the actual card number */</span>
<span class="cm-variable-2">$arr</span>[<span class="cm-variable">BANK_ACCOUNT_NUMBER</span>] <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">identitymind_hashBankRoutingAccount</span>(<span class="cm-string">"321076479"</span>, <span class="cm-string">"74600015199010"</span>);
<span class="cm-variable-2">$arr</span>[<span class="cm-variable">BANK_ACCOUNT_TOKEN</span>] <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-variable">identitymind_bankRoutingAccountToken</span>(<span class="cm-string">"321076479"</span>, <span class="cm-string">"74600015199010"</span>);

<span class="cm-comment">/* Turn the array into a JSON string to be used as the body of the POST */</span>
<span class="cm-variable-2">$data</span> <span class="cm-operator">=</span> <span class="cm-builtin">json_encode</span>(<span class="cm-variable-2">$arr</span>);
</div></code></pre></div></div>
<h1 class="heading heading-1 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="bank-account"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-bank-account" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Bank Account</div></h1>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="account-hash"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-account-hash" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Account Hash</div></h2>
<p>For a US bank account number concatenate the salt and the routing number and account number and pass that to the function to get account number hash.</p>
<p>For an international IBAN account number concatenate the salt and full IBAN account number and pass that to the function to get account number hash.</p>
<blockquote class="callout callout_warn" theme="🚧"><h3 class="callout-heading false"><span class="callout-icon">🚧</span><p>Normalization</p></h3><p>All spaces and dashes should be removed from the account number prior to hashing.</p></blockquote>
<blockquote class="callout callout_info" theme="📘"><h3 class="callout-heading false"><span class="callout-icon">📘</span><p>Sample Value</p></h3><p>For example, the salted bank account number hash for <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">321076479 74600015199010</span></code> is <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">3f57733f34b677294fed96efd440b8d9e7728fa5</span></code> and the hash for <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">SN12K00100152000025690007542</span></code> is <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">dd91898995dfef188eca122c5e0dd92f3aa34550</span></code>.  You can include this in your unit tests to verify your hashing implementation is correct.</p></blockquote>
<p>The account number hash should be included in the JSON string of the request to IdentityMind Transaction API in the field <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">pach</span></code>.</p>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="account-token"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-account-token" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Account Token</div></h2>
<p>For the bank account number token we recommend: </p>
<ul>
<li>For a US bank account number, the first 6 digits of the routing number, followed by XXXXXXXX and the last 4 digits of the account number </li>
<li>For an international, IBAN account number the first 6 digits of the account, followed by XXXXXXXX and the last 4 digits of the account number</li>
</ul>
<p>For example, the token for <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">321076479 74600015199010</span></code> is <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">321076XXXXXXXX9010</span></code> and the hash for <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">SN12K00100152000025690007542</span></code> is <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">SN12K0XXXXXXXX7542</span></code></p>
<p>The bank account number token should be included in the JSON string of the request to IdentityMind Transaction API in the field <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">ptoken</span></code>.</p>
<blockquote class="callout callout_info" theme="📘"><h3 class="callout-heading false"><span class="callout-icon">📘</span><p>Token</p></h3><p>The masked/tokenized number is only used with the user interface as a label for this Bank Account.  It is unique to you and can be in any format that conforms with your information security constraints.</p></blockquote>
<h1 class="heading heading-1 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="virtual-currencies"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-virtual-currencies" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Virtual Currencies</div></h1>
<p>Since virtual currency addresses are public information and do not need to be protected in the same way as a credit card number, these addresses are sent to the platform in clear text.</p>
<p>The token can be any value, including the clear text address, that will be meaningful to you when displayed in the user interface.</p>
<blockquote class="callout callout_info" theme="📘"><h3 class="callout-heading false"><span class="callout-icon">📘</span><p>Virtual Currency Risk Assessment</p></h3><p>Providing clear text virtual currency addresses to the platform allows the use of the Virtual Currency Risk Assessment service to evaluate fraud and compliance risk associated with an address.</p></blockquote>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="bitcoin-address"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-bitcoin-address" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Bitcoin Address</div></h2>
<p>A bitcoin address should be provided to the platform in either <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">1 address</span></code>, or <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">3 address</span></code>, or Bech32 format which are standard Base58 encodings of a public key, for example</p>
<pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">"pbc" : "1BVBVqr1ScffvamGdB9kzaJm52BJ3x6kq6"
"pbc" : "bc1qrp33g0q5c5txsp9arysrx4k6zdkfs4nce4xj0gdcccefvpysxf3qccfmv4"
</span></code></pre>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="ethereum-address"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-ethereum-address" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Ethereum Address</div></h2>
<p>An ethereum address should be provided to the platform in <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">0x</span></code> notation, for example</p>
<pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">"pbc" : "0x0472ec0185ebb8202f3d4ddb0226998889663cf2"
</span></code></pre>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="bitcoin-cash"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-bitcoin-cash" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Bitcoin Cash</div></h2>
<p>A bitcoin cash address should be provided to the platform starting with either <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">q</span></code> or <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">bitcoincash:</span></code>, for example</p>
<pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">"pbc" : "bitcoincash:pqkh9ahfj069qv8l6eysyufazpe4fdjq3u4hna323k"
</span></code></pre>
<h1 class="heading heading-1 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="paypal"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-pay-pal" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>PayPal</div></h1>
<p>PayPal account information is provided to the API in clear text.  Please reference the  <a href="/reference-link/transaction-monitoring-1" target="" title="">API specification</a> for the data fields that are available.</p>
<p>The API fields used for PayPal payment methods are as follows:</p>




















<div class="rdmd-table"><div class="rdmd-table-inner"><table><thead><tr><th style="text-align: left;"></th><th style="text-align: left;">Originator</th><th style="text-align: left;">Beneficiary</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td style="text-align: left;">For transactions facilitated with the PayPal Payer Email use:</td><td style="text-align: left;"><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">pppe</span></code></td><td style="text-align: left;"><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">dpppe</span></code></td></tr><tr><td style="text-align: left;">For transactions facilitated using the PayPal Payer ID use:</td><td style="text-align: left;"><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">pppi</span></code></td><td style="text-align: left;"><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">dpppi</span></code></td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>
<h1 class="heading heading-1 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="generic-payment"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-generic-payment" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Generic Payment</div></h1>
<p>The IdentityMind platform provides a mechanism to provide identifier that represent form of payments that are unique to your application, for example, an account number that represents a loyalty program account.</p>
<p>The API fields used in this case are <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">phash</span></code> and <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">ptoken</span></code>.   See  <a href="/reference-link/graph" target="" title="">API specification</a> for more details.</p>
<blockquote class="callout callout_info" theme="📘"><h3 class="callout-heading false"><span class="callout-icon">📘</span><p>Help</p></h3><p>Please contact support at IdentityMind to discuss the best way to model your custom payment types within the IdentityMind platform.</p></blockquote></div></div></div><input id="swagger-send-defaults" type="hidden" value=""></div><div class="hub-reference" id="page-data-field-formatting"><a class="anchor-page-title" id="data-field-formatting"></a><div class="hub-reference-section hub-reference-section-top"><div class="hub-reference-left"><header><a class="hub-reference-edit pull-right" href="/reference-edit/data-field-formatting"><i class="icon icon-register"></i>Suggest Edits</a><h2>Data Field Formatting</h2></header></div><div class="hub-reference-right">&nbsp;</div></div><div class="hub-reference-section"><div class="hub-reference-left"><div class="markdown-body"><p>Some data fields within the API require specific formatting conventions.  The formats are defined within the API specification itself, but for convenience and more specific details please see below.</p>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="payment-instrument-fields"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-payment-instrument-fields" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Payment Instrument Fields</div></h2>
<p>See <a href="/reference-link/payment-instrument-hashing" target="" title="">Payment Instrument Hashing</a> </p>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="assn-assn1-assn2"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-assn-assn-1-assn-2" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>assn, assn1, assn2</div></h2>
<p>The applicant's social security number or national identification number. It is a structured string defined as <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">[ISO-3166-1 (alpha-2):][national id]</span></code>.</p>
<p>For example </p>
<pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">"assn" : "US:123456789"
</span></code></pre>
<p>represents a United States Social Security Number. For backwards compatibility if no country code is provided then the identifier is assumed to be a US SSN.</p>
<p>Reference: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-2" target="" title="">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-2</a></p>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="dob"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-dob" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>dob</div></h2>
<p>Applicant's date of birth encoded as an ISO8601 date string (YYYY-MM-DD) or as a Unix epoch timestamp</p>
<pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">"dob" : "1998-02-27"
"dob" : "-100137600"
"dob" : 930528000
</span></code></pre>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="ph-pm-phn-pw"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-ph-pm-phn-pw" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>ph, pm, phn, pw</div></h2>
<p>While the phone number fields do not enforce any strict format it is recommended to</p>
<ul>
<li>include the full phone number including area code</li>
<li>if a non-US and Canada number include the country code</li>
</ul>
<pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">"ph" : "6505551212",
"pm" : "+353 86 123 4567"
</span></code></pre>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="memo1--memo99"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-memo-1-memo-99" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>memo1 ... memo99</div></h2>
<p>Memo fields are freeform text fields that you can use to upload custom data to the IdentityMind platform.   For example, you might upload some results from a third party provider that you already have integrated with your application and then use that data within your IdentityMind fraud rules.</p>
<pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">"memo1" : "42",
"memo70" : "gold star member"
</span></code></pre>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="image-data"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-image-data" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Image Data</div></h2>
<p>All image data is uploaded as as mimetype followed by a Base64 encoded string.</p>
<h3 class="heading heading-3 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="scandata-backsideimage"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-scan-data-backside-image" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>scanData, backsideImage</div></h3>
<pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">"scanData" : "image/jpeg;base64,/9j/4RnLRXhpZgAATU..."
"backsideImageData" : "image/jpeg;base64,R0lGODdhOAKRAfcAAAAAA...."
</span></code></pre>
<h3 class="heading heading-3 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="faceimages"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-face-images" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>faceImages</div></h3>
<p>The faceImages is a set of image files that are used for liveness testing.   They are encoded as a JSON array of Base64 images.</p>
<pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">"faceImages" : [ "image/jpeg;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUh....", 
                          "image/jpeg;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEU..." ]
</span></code></pre></div></div><div class="hub-reference-right"><div class="markdown-body"><p>Some data fields within the API require specific formatting conventions.  The formats are defined within the API specification itself, but for convenience and more specific details please see below.</p>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="payment-instrument-fields"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-payment-instrument-fields" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Payment Instrument Fields</div></h2>
<p>See <a href="/reference-link/payment-instrument-hashing" target="" title="">Payment Instrument Hashing</a> </p>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="assn-assn1-assn2"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-assn-assn-1-assn-2" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>assn, assn1, assn2</div></h2>
<p>The applicant's social security number or national identification number. It is a structured string defined as <code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">[ISO-3166-1 (alpha-2):][national id]</span></code>.</p>
<p>For example </p>
<pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">"assn" : "US:123456789"
</span></code></pre>
<p>represents a United States Social Security Number. For backwards compatibility if no country code is provided then the identifier is assumed to be a US SSN.</p>
<p>Reference: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-2" target="" title="">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-2</a></p>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="dob"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-dob" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>dob</div></h2>
<p>Applicant's date of birth encoded as an ISO8601 date string (YYYY-MM-DD) or as a Unix epoch timestamp</p>
<pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">"dob" : "1998-02-27"
"dob" : "-100137600"
"dob" : 930528000
</span></code></pre>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="ph-pm-phn-pw"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-ph-pm-phn-pw" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>ph, pm, phn, pw</div></h2>
<p>While the phone number fields do not enforce any strict format it is recommended to</p>
<ul>
<li>include the full phone number including area code</li>
<li>if a non-US and Canada number include the country code</li>
</ul>
<pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">"ph" : "6505551212",
"pm" : "+353 86 123 4567"
</span></code></pre>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="memo1--memo99"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-memo-1-memo-99" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>memo1 ... memo99</div></h2>
<p>Memo fields are freeform text fields that you can use to upload custom data to the IdentityMind platform.   For example, you might upload some results from a third party provider that you already have integrated with your application and then use that data within your IdentityMind fraud rules.</p>
<pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">"memo1" : "42",
"memo70" : "gold star member"
</span></code></pre>
<h2 class="heading heading-2 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="image-data"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-image-data" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Image Data</div></h2>
<p>All image data is uploaded as as mimetype followed by a Base64 encoded string.</p>
<h3 class="heading heading-3 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="scandata-backsideimage"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-scan-data-backside-image" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>scanData, backsideImage</div></h3>
<pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">"scanData" : "image/jpeg;base64,/9j/4RnLRXhpZgAATU..."
"backsideImageData" : "image/jpeg;base64,R0lGODdhOAKRAfcAAAAAA...."
</span></code></pre>
<h3 class="heading heading-3 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="faceimages"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-face-images" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>faceImages</div></h3>
<p>The faceImages is a set of image files that are used for liveness testing.   They are encoded as a JSON array of Base64 images.</p>
<pre><code class="rdmd-code lang-" data-lang="" name=""><button class="rdmd-code-copy fa"></button><span class="cm-s-neo">"faceImages" : [ "image/jpeg;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUh....", 
                          "image/jpeg;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEU..." ]
</span></code></pre></div></div></div><input id="swagger-send-defaults" type="hidden" value=""></div><div class="hub-reference" id="page-feedback-1"><a class="anchor-page-title" id="feedback-1"></a><div class="hub-reference-section hub-reference-section-top"><div class="hub-reference-left"><header><a class="hub-reference-edit pull-right" href="/reference-edit/feedback-1"><i class="icon icon-register"></i>Suggest Edits</a><h2>Feedback</h2></header></div><div class="hub-reference-right">&nbsp;</div></div><div class="hub-reference-section"><div class="hub-reference-left"><div class="markdown-body"><p>Providing feedback is an integral part of the IdentityMind platform. Feedback allows us to build more accurate models of entity reputations, strengthening the platform for all IDM users. Remember, no customer purchasing behavior or personal information is shared through our network, only reputation data. This enables you to identify good or bad users even if you’ve never done business with them before. Other than the reputation data itself, data from other IDM clients remain private. Clients cannot see where the reputation data originated.</p>
<p>The platform supports a rich set of API endpoints that allow clients to update the state of a transaction with resolution information. A simple example is the case of a payment transactions that ultimately results in a chargeback, in this situation the Payment Chargeback would be called.</p>
<p>Other examples of feedback include</p>
<ul>
<li>credit card auth responses</li>
<li>decision after analyst review</li>
<li>decision after user validation refund issued</li>
</ul>
<p>It is important to integrate with the feedback APIs because this information is used by the platform to improve your results in the following ways</p>
<ul>
<li>Update the reputation of the identities involved in the transaction, improving the accuracy of the identity verification in future transactions</li>
<li>Provide more context to your analyst when they are reviewing related transactions in the user interface</li>
<li>Provide "labels" for the machine learning models that are evaluating your transactions</li>
</ul>
<p>Full details of the API endpoints are provided <a href="/reference-link/transaction-feedback" target="" title="">here</a>, but the following provides an overview</p>
<h1 class="heading heading-1 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="bank-authorization-feedback"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-bank-authorization-feedback" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Bank Authorization Feedback</div></h1>
<p>Notify IdentityMind of the acceptance or rejection of the transaction that was previously analyzed with the given transaction ID.</p>
<p>POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/bank-accepted" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/bank-accepted</a></p>
<p>POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/bank-rejected" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/bank-rejected</a></p>
<h1 class="heading heading-1 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="merchant-final-resolution-feedback"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-merchant-final-resolution-feedback" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Merchant Final Resolution Feedback</div></h1>
<p>Provide feedback that the transaction has been accepted after review.<br>
POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/accepted" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/accepted</a></p>
<p>Provide feedback that the transaction has been rejected after review due to suspected fraud.<br>
POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/rejected" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/rejected</a></p>
<p>Provide feedback that the transaction has been rejected after review.<br>
POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/rejected-ok" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/rejected-ok</a></p>
<p>Provide feedback that the transaction has been accepted due to user validation.<br>
POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/accepted-user-validated" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/accepted-user-validated</a></p>
<p>Provide feedback that the transaction has been rejected due to user validation failure.<br>
POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/rejected-user-failed-validation" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/rejected-user-failed-validation</a></p>
<p>Provide feedback that the transaction has been accepted by default.<br>
POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/accepted-default" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/accepted-default</a></p>
<p>Provide feedback that the transaction has been rejected by default.<br>
POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/rejected-default" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/rejected-default</a></p>
<h1 class="heading heading-1 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="transaction-neutralrefund-notification"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-transaction-neutral-refund-notification" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Transaction Neutral/Refund Notification</div></h1>
<p>Notify IdentityMind that a refund occurred on a transaction.</p>
<p>POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/refund-ok" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/refund-ok</a></p>
<p>POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/refund-fraud" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/refund-fraud</a></p>
<p>POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/refund-partial-ok" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/refund-partial-ok</a></p>
<p>POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/refund-partial-fraud" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/refund-partial-fraud</a></p>
<p>The “refund-ok” URL should be used when the merchant believes that the refund is legitimate.<br>
The “refund-fraud” URL should be used when the merchant believes there is fraud, but a refund is being made to avoid a later chargeback.</p></div></div><div class="hub-reference-right"><div class="markdown-body"><p>Providing feedback is an integral part of the IdentityMind platform. Feedback allows us to build more accurate models of entity reputations, strengthening the platform for all IDM users. Remember, no customer purchasing behavior or personal information is shared through our network, only reputation data. This enables you to identify good or bad users even if you’ve never done business with them before. Other than the reputation data itself, data from other IDM clients remain private. Clients cannot see where the reputation data originated.</p>
<p>The platform supports a rich set of API endpoints that allow clients to update the state of a transaction with resolution information. A simple example is the case of a payment transactions that ultimately results in a chargeback, in this situation the Payment Chargeback would be called.</p>
<p>Other examples of feedback include</p>
<ul>
<li>credit card auth responses</li>
<li>decision after analyst review</li>
<li>decision after user validation refund issued</li>
</ul>
<p>It is important to integrate with the feedback APIs because this information is used by the platform to improve your results in the following ways</p>
<ul>
<li>Update the reputation of the identities involved in the transaction, improving the accuracy of the identity verification in future transactions</li>
<li>Provide more context to your analyst when they are reviewing related transactions in the user interface</li>
<li>Provide "labels" for the machine learning models that are evaluating your transactions</li>
</ul>
<p>Full details of the API endpoints are provided <a href="/reference-link/transaction-feedback" target="" title="">here</a>, but the following provides an overview</p>
<h1 class="heading heading-1 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="bank-authorization-feedback"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-bank-authorization-feedback" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Bank Authorization Feedback</div></h1>
<p>Notify IdentityMind of the acceptance or rejection of the transaction that was previously analyzed with the given transaction ID.</p>
<p>POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/bank-accepted" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/bank-accepted</a></p>
<p>POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/bank-rejected" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/bank-rejected</a></p>
<h1 class="heading heading-1 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="merchant-final-resolution-feedback"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-merchant-final-resolution-feedback" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Merchant Final Resolution Feedback</div></h1>
<p>Provide feedback that the transaction has been accepted after review.<br>
POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/accepted" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/accepted</a></p>
<p>Provide feedback that the transaction has been rejected after review due to suspected fraud.<br>
POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/rejected" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/rejected</a></p>
<p>Provide feedback that the transaction has been rejected after review.<br>
POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/rejected-ok" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/rejected-ok</a></p>
<p>Provide feedback that the transaction has been accepted due to user validation.<br>
POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/accepted-user-validated" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/accepted-user-validated</a></p>
<p>Provide feedback that the transaction has been rejected due to user validation failure.<br>
POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/rejected-user-failed-validation" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/rejected-user-failed-validation</a></p>
<p>Provide feedback that the transaction has been accepted by default.<br>
POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/accepted-default" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/accepted-default</a></p>
<p>Provide feedback that the transaction has been rejected by default.<br>
POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/rejected-default" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/rejected-default</a></p>
<h1 class="heading heading-1 header-scroll" align=""><div class="heading-anchor anchor waypoint" id="transaction-neutralrefund-notification"></div><div class="heading-text"><div id="section-transaction-neutral-refund-notification" class="heading-anchor_backwardsCompatibility"></div>Transaction Neutral/Refund Notification</div></h1>
<p>Notify IdentityMind that a refund occurred on a transaction.</p>
<p>POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/refund-ok" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/refund-ok</a></p>
<p>POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/refund-fraud" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/refund-fraud</a></p>
<p>POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/refund-partial-ok" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/refund-partial-ok</a></p>
<p>POST <a href="https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/%3Ctransaction_id%3E/refund-partial-fraud" target="" title="">https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/transaction/&lt;transaction_id&gt;/refund-partial-fraud</a></p>
<p>The “refund-ok” URL should be used when the merchant believes that the refund is legitimate.<br>
The “refund-fraud” URL should be used when the merchant believes there is fraud, but a refund is being made to avoid a later chargeback.</p></div></div></div><input id="swagger-send-defaults" data-json="[{&quot;_id&quot;:&quot;607454132b80da024fc219d3&quot;,&quot;version&quot;:&quot;607454132b80da024fc21b08&quot;,&quot;project&quot;:&quot;5bd8dbd1c9711600503f7231&quot;,&quot;category&quot;:&quot;607454132b80da024fc219ad&quot;,&quot;user&quot;:&quot;5bbf7d0331683d00033cd978&quot;,&quot;updates&quot;:[],&quot;next&quot;:{&quot;pages&quot;:[],&quot;description&quot;:&quot;&quot;},&quot;createdAt&quot;:&quot;2018-11-20T18:57:38.995Z&quot;,&quot;link_external&quot;:false,&quot;link_url&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;sync_unique&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;hidden&quot;:false,&quot;api&quot;:{&quot;results&quot;:{&quot;codes&quot;:[{&quot;status&quot;:200,&quot;language&quot;:&quot;json&quot;,&quot;code&quot;:&quot;{}&quot;,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;&quot;},{&quot;status&quot;:400,&quot;language&quot;:&quot;json&quot;,&quot;code&quot;:&quot;{}&quot;,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;&quot;}]},&quot;auth&quot;:&quot;required&quot;,&quot;params&quot;:[],&quot;url&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;method&quot;:&quot;get&quot;},&quot;isReference&quot;:true,&quot;order&quot;:0,&quot;body&quot;:&quot;The IdentityMind platform exposes a REST interface with JSON encoded data. Our clients send us transactional information (payments, transfers, KYC, KYB) that we match against our identity database and evaluate against the risk and compliance policy the client has created.\n\nA typical merchant / IdentityMind interaction to validate a transaction is shown below:\n[block:image]\n{\n  \&quot;images\&quot;: [\n    {\n      \&quot;image\&quot;: [\n        \&quot;https://files.readme.io/bd2d2c0-v9qj1DP.png\&quot;,\n        \&quot;v9qj1DP.png\&quot;,\n        800,\n        500,\n        \&quot;#228489\&quot;\n      ]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n[/block]\nThe APIs are fully specified in [swagger/oas](https://swagger.io) and the raw [swagger.json is available from the sandbox environment](https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/swagger.json).\n\n# Authentication\n\nIdentityMind uses an SSL Server certificate for the client to authenticate the service. The merchant is authenticated using HTTP basic access authentication (over HTTPS) via an API name and key that is supplied when the merchant registers for the service.\n\nBasic access authentication is a way for users to provide a username and password during a request. The request is encoded in Base64 and sent in the headers of each HTTP request. To create an authorization field the username and password are combined in a string, separated by a colon (username:password), encoded in Base64, then sent with a description notifying the server of the authorization method. An example HTTP request, along with the authentication request, will look like this:\n[block:code]\n{\n  \&quot;codes\&quot;: [\n    {\n      \&quot;code\&quot;: \&quot;curl --request POST \\\\\\n  --url https://sandbox.identitymind.com/im/account/transfer \\\\\\n  --header 'accept: application/json' \\\\\\n  --header 'authorization: Basic Y2xpZW50bmFtZTpjbGllbnRuYW1l' \\\\\\n  --header 'content-type: application/json' \\\\\\n  --data '{ \\n  \\\&quot;man\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;jdoe\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;soc\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;facebook\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;tea\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;jdoe1964@gmail.com\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;bc\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;Jersey City\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;bco\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;US\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;bfn\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;John\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;bln\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;Doe\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;bz\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;07304\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;bs\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;NJ\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;bsn\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;123 1st St\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;dft\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;AU\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;dfp\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;187ASDSA&amp;#EAD129E…\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;ip\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;72.160.112.466\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;pbc\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;89756415ac…\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;ptoken\\\&quot;  : \\\&quot;4697XXXXXX000e\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;dpbc\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;8ad0e1256874…\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;dptoken\\\&quot;  : \\\&quot;511988714XXXXXX000e\\\&quot;,\\\\\\n  \\\&quot;amt\\\&quot; : \\\&quot;120.00\\\&quot;\\\\\\n}'\&quot;,\n      \&quot;language\&quot;: \&quot;curl\&quot;\n    }\n  ]\n}\n[/block]\n# Integration Environments\n\nThe IdentityMind platform supports the following environments for integration testing and production deployment:\n\nhttps://sandbox.identitymind.com - A mock environment suitable for initial integration tests and regression testing.  The transactional data is cleared on a daily basis.  See [Sandbox Environment](ref:sandbox-environment) for more details.\nhttps://staging.identitymind.com - A fully featured environment suitable for building and testing the anti fraud policy. Staging permits limited access to 3rd party partners. Transactional data is cleared on a weekly basis.\nhttps://edna.identitymind.com - Production environment.\n\n\n[block:callout]\n{\n  \&quot;type\&quot;: \&quot;info\&quot;,\n  \&quot;title\&quot;: \&quot;Credentials\&quot;,\n  \&quot;body\&quot;: \&quot;IdentityMind provides unique credentials for each of these environments.\&quot;\n}\n[/block]\n\n[block:callout]\n{\n  \&quot;type\&quot;: \&quot;warning\&quot;,\n  \&quot;body\&quot;: \&quot;Do not send production data to the Sandbox environment. Likewise, test data should not be sent to the Production environment. The Staging environment can be used for both real and test data. The Staging environment should not, however, be treated as a production system as data sent to Staging is deleted every week.\&quot;,\n  \&quot;title\&quot;: \&quot;Production Data\&quot;\n}\n[/block]\n\n[block:callout]\n{\n  \&quot;type\&quot;: \&quot;warning\&quot;,\n  \&quot;title\&quot;: \&quot;Credit Card / Bank Account Numbers\&quot;,\n  \&quot;body\&quot;: \&quot;Clear text credit card and bank account numbers should never be sent to IdentityMind. Instead, IdentityMind uses a cryptographically secure hash to have a unique representation of each number. IdentityMind provides the required utilities to generate these hashes. See [Payment Instrument Hashing](reference#payment-instrument-hashing) for more details.\&quot;\n}\n[/block]\n\n[block:callout]\n{\n  \&quot;type\&quot;: \&quot;danger\&quot;,\n  \&quot;title\&quot;: \&quot;Missing Data\&quot;,\n  \&quot;body\&quot;: \&quot;The more data that is provided, the better the performance of the platform will be.  However most fields within the API are optional. \\n\\nIf you do not have a piece of information, if, for example, the customer didn't provide a phone number, then simply leave that field out of the JSON data. In particular, **do not include fake or placeholder data** since this will potentially cause unwanted correlations in the results.\&quot;\n}\n[/block]\n\n# Feedback\n\nThe IdentityMind platform supports [a rich set of API endpoints](ref:transaction-feedback)  which allow clients to update the state of a transaction with resolution information. A simple example is the case of a payment transaction which ultimately results in a chargeback, in this situation the [Payment Chargeback](ref:receivechargebacknotification) would be called.\n\nOther examples of feedback include:\n* credit card auth responses\n* decision after analyst review\n* decision after user validation refund issued\n\nIt is important to integrate with the feedback APIs because this information is used by the platform to improve your results in the following ways:\n* Update the reputation of the identities involved in the transaction, improving the accuracy of the identity verification in future transactions\n* Provide more context to your analyst when they are reviewing related transactions in the user interface\n* Provide \&quot;labels\&quot; for the machine
